\begin_layout Subsection
Equivalence of integrals and measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that while in Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:existenceUniquenessLebesgueIntegral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 we constructed the integral from a seemingly more primitive concept of
 a measure, it turns out that a measure can be constructed out a linear
 functional on the space of measurable functions such that the functional
 is the integral with respect to the measure we have constructed.
 In this sense, measures and integrals are really equivalent.
 At this point, this may seem to be a trivial observation (and the proof
 of this result is indeed trivial); this shift of perspective, however,
 offers powerful simplifications to questions concerning the existence and
 uniqueness of measures.
 Indeed, our approach to product measures in Chapter 6 would rely on this
 insight, allowing us to prove both the existence of product measures, and
 the representation of integrals with respect to product measures as iterated
 integrals, in a single stroke.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:integralMeasureEquivalence"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F\right)$
\end_inset

 be a measurable space and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda:\nonnegMeasurableFunctions\longrightarrow\left[0,\infty\right]
\]

\end_inset

be a linear functional that satisfies monotone convergence i.e for any sequence
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\in\measurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\leq f_{n+1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f:=\lim_{n\to\infty}f_{n}\in\F$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda\left(f\right)=\lim_{n\to\infty}\Lambda\left(f_{n}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Further, suppose there exists a function 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in\nonnegMeasurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(g\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Then the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda:\F\longrightarrow\left[0,\infty\right]
\]

\end_inset

given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda\left(A\right):=\Lambda\left(\indicate_{A}\right)
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F$
\end_inset

 is a measure and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is the integral with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First, note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Lambda\left(g\right) & =\Lambda\left(g+\indicate_{\emptyset}\right)\\
 & =\Lambda\left(g\right)+\Lambda\left(\indicate_{\emptyset}\right)\\
 & =\Lambda\left(g\right)+\lambda\left(\emptyset\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

by linearity and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda\left(g\right)<\infty$
\end_inset

, we can subtract it from both sides to deduce 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\left(\emptyset\right)=0.$
\end_inset

 To establish countable additivity, note that for a disjoint collection
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{n}\in\F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(\bigcup_{n\in\N}A_{n}\right) & =\Lambda\left(\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\indicate_{A_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\Lambda\left(\indicate_{A_{n}}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\lambda\left(A_{n}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the first equality is by (an extension of) Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:indicatorFunctionsArbitraryOperations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and the second by linearity and monotone convergence.
 Of course, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 satisfies the properties of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:existenceUniquenessLebesgueIntegral"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, it is the unique integral induced by the measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

; this completes the proof.
\end_layout

