\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark*
Corresponding to the notion of almost-everywhere equality of measurable
 functions, there's a notion of almost-everywhere equality of sets.
 Recall from set theory that the symmetric difference of two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 is given
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\Delta B:=\left(A\setminus B\right)\bigcup\left(B\setminus A\right)
\]

\end_inset

Given a measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

on some measurable space 
\begin_inset Formula $\measurablespace$
\end_inset

 and sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\in\F$
\end_inset

, we say 
\begin_inset Formula $A\stackrel{\mu-\text{a.e}}{=}B$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(A\Delta B\right)=0.$
\end_inset

 Of course, in the spirit of Theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:integralMeasureEquivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this definition must coincide with the one for measurable functions in
