\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:subsubSequence"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 be a topological space.
 The sequence
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N}\in\X$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\X$
\end_inset

 if and only if every subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 has a further subsequence that converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $x.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Convergence implies subsequential convergence for every subseqeuence (and
 in particulary, subsubsequences).
 Conversely, suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}\nrightarrow x$
\end_inset

.
 Then there's an open set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U\in\tau}$
\end_inset

 that contains 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that there are infinitely many elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n}$
\end_inset

 outside 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, there exists some subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n_{k}}\notin\mathcal{U}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 Then no subsequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{n_{k}}$
\end_inset

 converges to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

