\begin_layout Subsection
Uniform integrability and uniform absolute continuity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dominated convergence theorem says that for sequence of random variables
 that are dominated by an integrable function, pointwise convergence implies
 convergence in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We would like to extend this notion more broadly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:uniformIntegrability"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 be a measure space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\measurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 be a collection of measurable functions.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
uniformly integrable 
\emph default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}}<\epsilon
\]

\end_inset

for every 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:uniformAbsoluteContinuity"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 be a measure space and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\measurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 be a collection of measurable functions.
 We say 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
uniformly absolutely continuous 
\emph default
if for every 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 there exists a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\in\F,\mu(F)<\delta\implies\lvert\lebInt{\mu}{f\indicate_{F}}\rvert<\epsilon.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "rem:uniformAbsoluteContinuity"

\end_inset

Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is a trivial class i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}=\{f\}$
\end_inset

, then the absolute continuity property always holds as observed in Proposition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:densities"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and Remark 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "rem:absoluteContinuity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Of course, it is not clear that this 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon-\delta$
\end_inset

 characterization of absolute continuity is the same as the one discussed
 in that remark; later on in Chapter 6 (see Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:epsdeltaAbsContinuity"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) we show they are indeed equiavelent for finite measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:finiteMeasureUniformIntegrability"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 be a finite measure space i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\X)<\infty.$
\end_inset

 Then a class of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\measurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 is uniformly integrable if and only if it is uniformly absolutely continuous
 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sup_{f\in\mathcal{C}}\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert}<\infty.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}\subseteq\measurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 is uniformly integrable.
 Fix some 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and observe that by uniform integrability there is some 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}}<\frac{\epsilon}{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $F\in\F$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lvert\lebInt{\mu}{f\indicate_{F}}\rvert & \leq\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{F}}\\
 & =\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\left(\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}+\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert\leq M\}}\right)\indicate_{F}}\\
 & =\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}\indicate_{F}}+\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert\leq M\}}\indicate_{F}}\\
 & \leq\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}}+\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert\leq M\}}\indicate_{F}}\\
 & \leq\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}}+\lebInt{\mu}{M\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert\leq M\}}\indicate_{F}}\\
 & \leq\frac{\epsilon}{2}+M\mu(\{\lvert f\rvert\leq M\}\cap F)\\
 & \leq\frac{\epsilon}{2}+M\mu(F)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where all the inequalities follow by the monotonicity of the integral.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{\epsilon}{2M}$
\end_inset

 then shows uniform absolute continuity.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $F=\X$
\end_inset

 then yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert}\leq\frac{\epsilon}{2}+M\mu(\X)
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 which gives us the boundedness in 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Conversely, assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{C}$
\end_inset

 is uniformly absolutely continuous and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sup_{f\in\mathcal{C}}\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert}<\infty.$
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 and note that there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\in\F,\mu(F)<\delta\implies\lvert\lebInt{\mu}{f\indicate_{F}}\rvert<\epsilon$
\end_inset

.
 Note that by Markov's inequality
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu\left(\lvert f\rvert>M\right)\leq\frac{\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert}}{M}.
\]

\end_inset

for any 
\begin_inset Formula $M\in\N$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert}<\infty,$
\end_inset

we can take 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 large enough to so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\lvert f\rvert>M\right)<\delta$
\end_inset

 which by uniform absolute continuity implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lvert\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\lvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}}\rvert=\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\lvert\indicate_{\{\lvert f\rvert>M\}}}<\epsilon.$
\end_inset

 This shows uniform integrability, completing the proof.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above implies that integrable functions on finite measure spaces are
 uniformly integrable on their own.
 Classes of uniformly integrable functions are preserved under linear combinatio
ns.
\end_layout

