Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\X,\F,\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 be a finite measure space i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\X)<\infty.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N}\in\measurableFunctions$
\end_inset

 are uniformly integrable and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\stackrel{\mu}{\longrightarrow}f$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Lp1{\mu}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{n}\stackrel{\mathcal{L}^{1}}{\longrightarrow}f.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\stackrel{\mu}{\longrightarrow}f$
\end_inset

 then by Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:convInMeasureImpliesSubsequenceAE"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 there exists some subsequence 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n_{j}}\stackrel{\text{a.e}}{\longrightarrow}f$
\end_inset

.
 By Fatou's lemma and the fact that absolute value is continuous, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f\rvert}=\lebInt{\mu}{\liminf_{j\to\infty}\lvert f_{n_{j}}\rvert}\leq\liminf_{j\to\infty}\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f_{n_{j}}\rvert}\leq\sup_{n\in\N}\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert f_{n}\rvert}<\infty
\]

\end_inset

where the last inequality follows by Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:finiteMeasureUniformIntegrability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which shows 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\Lp1{\mu}.$
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ f_{n}\right\} _{n\in\N},\left\{ f\right\} $
\end_inset

 are uniformly integrable, 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{n}:=f_{n}-f$
\end_inset

 is uniormly integrable by Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:uniformlyIntegrableLinearCombination"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Note that by uniform absolute continuity, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

, there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta>0$
\end_inset

 such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\F:P(A)<\delta\implies\lebInt{\mu}{\lvert g_{n}\rvert\indicate_{A}}<\frac{\epsilon}{2}.$
